🧪 Demonstration: MIDRC BIH Federated Data Mesh (Pilot Notebook)¶

Purpose. This notebook showcases a compact, end-to-end federated analysis workflowspanning discovery access harmonization representation learning evaluation reportingto illustrate how the MIDRC Biomedical Informatics Hub (BIH) enables cross-repository research without centralizing raw data.

🎯 Objectives¶

  • Query at least two datasets located in separate, BIH-interoperable repositories
    (we use Stanford Stanford AIMI MRA-MIDAS and TCIA CPTAC-CM as low-hanging fruit)
  • Pull subsets into a MIDRC BIH workspace for analysis & visualization
  • Harmonize with granular metadata, Common Data Elements (CDEs), and the MIDRC Common Data Model (CDM)
    (with hooks to integrate BDF harmonization tools as they mature)

🧰 Datasets & Access¶

Source Modality Access Content (pilot) Notes
Stanford AIMI MRA-MIDAS (Stanford) Dermoscopic/clinical photos SAS URL (read-list) Excel metadata + image files
TCIA CPTAC-CM CT / MR / PT (DICOM) NBIA v1/v4 APIs Rich DICOM tags; series/instance granularity

Both are accessed in place via public endpoints; only manifests and pilot subsets are staged in the BIH workspace.

🗺️ Workflow Overview¶

  1. Discovery & Access

    • Enumerate TCIA series via NBIA API (v1 JSON/CSV fallback to v4).
    • Enumerate AIMI blobs via SAS; stage a pilot set.

  2. Workspace Pull

    • Download a small, representative sample from each source.
    • Build manifests:
      • midas_manifest.csv (images, lesion IDs, diagnosis bin)
      • cptac_cm_png_manifest.json (series UID, modality, body part, PNG previews, captions)

  3. Harmonization (BIH/MIDRC)

    • Normalize identifiers (series_uid, patient_id, lesion_id) and key fields (modality, body_part, series_desc).
    • Map to CDE/CDM-like columns; preserve provenance (source, file paths, access route).
    • Provide plug-points for BDF harmonizers/CDM mappers.

  4. Representation Learning

    • CLIP (ViT-B/32) embeddings for MIDAS photos (512-D).
    • ResNet50 features (2048-D) for TCIA slices window/normalize PNG reps.
    • Ridge map from radiologyCLIP-text space using auto-generated captions; normalize to 512-D.

  5. Shared Space & Visualization

    • PCA 128-D shared space (optionally append label anchors).
    • Fast UMAP for 2-D projection (subset-fit + transform); qualitative panels (top/bottom series).

  6. Evaluation & Reporting

    • Train Logistic Regression on MIDAS (5-fold AUROC/PR-AUC; calibration + permutation test).
    • Score CPTAC series; summarize distributions by modality / body part with bootstrap CIs.
    • Emit figures, tables, and a compact final report (outputs/final_report.md).

🧱 What “Harmonization” Means Here¶

  • Aligns identifiers & semantics to BIH/MIDRC expectations.
  • Preserves traceability (raw paths, access pattern, source metadata).
  • Stays tool-agnostic, so you can swap in BDF utilities and CDM mappers with minimal refactoring.

Design Choice: Keep manifests simple & auditable (CSV/JSON) so they are easy to diff, share, and reproduce across BIH workspaces.

📦 Expected Artifacts¶

  • Manifests: midas_manifest.csv, cptac_cm_png_manifest.json, pilot DICOM CSV
  • Embeddings: midas_clip_img_512.npy, cptac_resnet50_2048.npy, mapped cptac_clip_mapped_512.npy
  • Shared Space: midas_128.npy, cptac_128.npy
  • Models & Scores: midas_calibrated_lr.joblib, cptac_scores_calibrated.csv
  • Diagnostics: UMAP plots, histograms, reliability & permutation figures
  • Report: outputs/final_report.md

✅ Ready-to-Run Checklist¶

  • [ ] Access confirmed for AIMI SAS URL (valid se, sig)
  • [ ] TCIA NBIA API reachable (v1 JSON/CSV or v4 fallback)
  • [ ] Python env meets requirements (NumPy/Sklearn/PyTorch/Open-CLIP; pinned where needed)
  • [ ] Sufficient local disk for pilot PNGs/DICOMs and embeddings
  • [ ] (Optional) BDF harmonization tools available in path

⚠️ Scope & Limitations (Pilot)¶

  • Small, curated subsets for speed; not a benchmark.
  • Simple models (CLIP + linear/ridge/logistic); upgrade to modality-aware encoders and subject-level CV as next steps.
  • No PHI; all access adheres to repository governance.

✨ Takeaway¶

This notebook demonstrates how a BIH-style federated mesh lets you compose multi-repository, multi-modality analyses by standardizing metadata & CDEs, keeping provenance, and enabling repeatable, workspace-local computewithout moving the worlds data.

Fetch CPTAC-CM series list from TCIA (robust to API variants)¶

Goal. Retrieve all imaging series for the CPTAC-CM collection from TCIA, handling multiple API paths and formats so the notebook keeps working even if one endpoint changes.

Inputs¶

  • Collection: CPTAC-CM
  • Base endpoint: https://services.cancerimagingarchive.net/

Method (fallback order)¶

  1. NBIA v1 JSON
    .../nbia-api/services/v1/getSeries?Collection=CPTAC-CM&format=json
  2. NBIA v1 CSV
    .../nbia-api/services/v1/getSeries?Collection=CPTAC-CM&format=csv
  3. TCIA v4 JSON (fallback)
    .../services/v4/TCIA/query/getSeries?Collection=CPTAC-CM&format=json

The function tries each path in order and returns the first successful response as a pandas DataFrame, along with a short tag indicating which path succeeded (e.g., v1/json).

Key columns (used later)¶

  • SeriesInstanceUID (primary key)
  • StudyInstanceUID, Modality, SeriesDate, SeriesDescription, BodyPartExamined, SeriesNumber, ImageCount
  • Manufacturer, ManufacturerModelName, SoftwareVersions
  • LicenseURI, CollectionURI, DateReleased

Outputs¶

  • Console message: CPTAC-CM: <N> series via <path_used>
  • Preview of the first 3 rows (schema sanity check)

Why this matters¶

A robust, schema-stable series table ensures downstream stepsDICOMPNG conversion, stratified summaries, and scoringcan reliably join on SeriesInstanceUID without breaking when an API format changes.

def get_series_any(collection):
    # v1 JSON
    r = requests.get(f"{TCIA_V1}/getSeries",
                     params={"Collection": collection, "format":"json"}, timeout=120)
    if r.ok and r.text.strip():
        try:
            return pd.DataFrame(r.json()), "v1/json"
        except Exception:
            pass
    # v1 CSV
    r = requests.get(f"{TCIA_V1}/getSeries",
                     params={"Collection": collection, "format":"csv"}, timeout=120)
    if r.ok and r.text.strip():
        try:
            return pd.read_csv(io.StringIO(r.text)), "v1/csv"
        except Exception:
            pass
    # v4 JSON
    r = requests.get("https://services.cancerimagingarchive.net/services/v4/TCIA/query/getSeries",
                     params={"Collection": collection, "format":"json"}, timeout=120)
    r.raise_for_status()
    return pd.DataFrame(r.json()), "v4/json"

Summarize CPTAC-CM series by modality¶

What this cell does

  • Makes a working copy of series_df.
  • Chooses FileSize as the size column if it exists (otherwise skips size math).
  • Groups rows by Modality and computes:
    • n_series: count of series (SeriesInstanceUID)
    • n_patients: number of unique patients (PatientID)
    • est_gb: total FileSize summed (missing values treated as 0) and converted to GB

Why

  • Gives a quick sense of how the dataset is distributed across CT / MR / PT and how large each subset is on disk.

Output columns

  • Modality PT, CT, or MR.
  • n_series number of series for that modality.
  • n_patients unique patient count contributing to those series.
  • est_gb approximate total size in gigabytes (NaN if FileSize unavailable).

Use this summary to plan downloading/processing resources (e.g., CT dominates both series count and storage).

Build a small pilot subset with diverse series¶

Goal Create a compact, representative subset of CPTAC-CM series for quick local experiments, while limiting redundancy (too many near-duplicate sequences from the same patient).

Steps

  1. Copy source: work from series_df.
  2. Helper pick_distinct(g, n, per_patient_cap=2)
    • Sorts a group by SeriesDescription.
    • Keeps at most per_patient_cap series per patient.
    • De-duplicates by the pair (PatientID, normalized SeriesDescription) to avoid repeated sequences.
    • Stops after selecting n rows.
  3. Split by modality: make ct_df, pt_df, mr_df.
  4. Sample per modality:
    • pilot_ct: 16 CT series, 2 per patient.
    • pilot_pt: 8 PT series, 2 per patient.
    • pilot_mr: MR is concentrated in one patient, so pick distinct SeriesDescription (up to 6).
  5. Concatenate the three modality subsets into pilot and print counts.

Why this design

  • Ensures coverage across CT / PT / MR.
  • Limits per-patient dominance and repeated sequences.
  • Produces a small set thats fast to download and process.

Optional

  • If FileSize is available, report an approximate download size in GB for the pilot.
In [28]:
df = series_df.copy()

# helpers
def pick_distinct(g, n, per_patient_cap=2):
    out = []
    seen = set()
    per_pat = {}
    for _, r in g.sort_values("SeriesDescription", na_position="last").iterrows():
        pid = (r.get("PatientID") or r.get("PatientId") or "").strip()
        desc = str(r.get("SeriesDescription", "")).strip().lower()
        key = (pid, desc)
        if per_pat.get(pid, 0) >= per_patient_cap:
            continue
        if key in seen:
            continue  # avoid many repeats of the same sequence
        out.append(r)
        seen.add(key)
        per_pat[pid] = per_pat.get(pid, 0) + 1
        if len(out) >= n:
            break
    return pd.DataFrame(out)

ct_df = df[df["Modality"]=="CT"]
pt_df = df[df["Modality"]=="PT"]
mr_df = df[df["Modality"]=="MR"]

pilot_ct = pick_distinct(ct_df, n=16, per_patient_cap=2)
pilot_pt = pick_distinct(pt_df, n=8,  per_patient_cap=2)
# MR is all one patient  just take distinct sequences
pilot_mr = (
    mr_df.drop_duplicates(["SeriesDescription"])
         .head(6)   # choose 46; adjust as you like
)

pilot = pd.concat([pilot_ct, pilot_pt, pilot_mr], ignore_index=True)
print("Pilot counts:\n", pilot["Modality"].value_counts(), "\n")
print("Total series:", len(pilot))

# Optional: estimate size
if "FileSize" in pilot.columns:
    print(f"Estimated download size: ~{pilot['FileSize'].fillna(0).sum()/1e9:.1f} GB")

Download a pilot set from TCIA (resumable + robust) and build a manifest¶

Goal. Reliably fetch a handful of CPTAC-CM series from TCIAs NBIA v1 API with retry/back-off and byte-range resume, then extract files and write a CSV manifest for downstream slice/PNG generation.

Endpoints & paths¶

  • Base API: NBIA_V1 = https://services.cancerimagingarchive.net/nbia-api/services/v1
  • Output root: ./data/tcia/CPTAC-CM_pilot/ (one subfolder per SeriesInstanceUID)

Reliability features¶

  • Session with retries (make_session)
    • Uses urllib3.Retry with total/connect/read=8, backoff_factor=0.8.
    • Retries on 502/503/504.
    • Works with old/new urllib3 (allowed_methods vs method_whitelist).
  • Content length probe (head_size)
    • HEAD /getImage?SeriesInstanceUID=... to read Content-Length for progress bars and integrity checks.
  • Resumable download (download_series_zip)
    • Streams GET /getImage to *.partial file with Range: bytes=... when resuming.
    • Handles common transient errors: SSL, chunked encoding, connection resets, read timeouts.
    • Exponential backoff between attempts (up to max_retries=10).
    • If server ignores Range (status 200), restarts from zero.
    • Validation:
      • If remote size known compare bytes downloaded.
      • Else try opening as ZIP and testzip(); on success, rename to final *.zip.

On success, the function returns the path to the final ZIP; on repeated failure it raises with the partial file path for manual inspection.

Extraction & execution¶

  • extract_zip unzips each series into its dedicated folder.

# %pip install --quiet requests tqdm
NBIA_V1 = "https://services.cancerimagingarchive.net/nbia-api/services/v1"
OUT = Path("./data/tcia/CPTAC-CM_pilot"); OUT.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)

# --- session with retries (works on old urllib3 too) ---
def make_session():
    s = requests.Session()
    try:
        retry = Retry(total=8, connect=8, read=8, backoff_factor=0.8,
                      status_forcelist=(502,503,504), allowed_methods=frozenset(['GET']))
    except TypeError:
        # older urllib3 uses method_whitelist
        retry = Retry(total=8, connect=8, read=8, backoff_factor=0.8,
                      status_forcelist=(502,503,504), method_whitelist=frozenset(['GET']))
    s.mount("https://", HTTPAdapter(max_retries=retry, pool_connections=4, pool_maxsize=8))
    return s

def head_size(session, uid):
    r = session.head(f"{NBIA_V1}/getImage",
                     params={"SeriesInstanceUID": uid},
                     headers={"Connection":"close","Accept-Encoding":"identity"},
                     timeout=60)
    r.raise_for_status()
    try:
        return int(r.headers.get("Content-Length","0"))
    except Exception:
        return 0

def download_series_zip(series_uid: str, out_dir: Path, chunk=256*1024, max_retries=10):
    """
    Resumable, retrying downloader to avoid [SSL: DECRYPTION_FAILED_OR_BAD_RECORD_MAC].
    """
    out_dir.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    final = out_dir / f"{series_uid}.zip"
    if final.exists():
        return final
    partial = out_dir / f"{series_uid}.partial"

    ses = make_session()
    size_remote = 0
    try:
        size_remote = head_size(ses, series_uid)
    except Exception:
        pass

    bytes_done = partial.stat().st_size if partial.exists() else 0
    pbar = tqdm(total=size_remote or 0, initial=bytes_done, unit="B", unit_scale=True, desc=series_uid)

    sleep = 1.0
    for attempt in range(1, max_retries+1):
        headers = {"Connection":"close","Accept-Encoding":"identity"}
        if bytes_done:
            headers["Range"] = f"bytes={bytes_done}-"

        try:
            with ses.get(f"{NBIA_V1}/getImage",
                         params={"SeriesInstanceUID": series_uid},
                         headers=headers, stream=True, timeout=(20, 120)) as r:
                # Some servers ignore Range  start over
                if bytes_done and r.status_code == 200:
                    bytes_done = 0
                    if partial.exists():
                        partial.unlink()
                    pbar.reset(total=size_remote or 0)

                r.raise_for_status()
                with open(partial, "ab") as f:
                    for ch in r.iter_content(chunk_size=chunk):
                        if not ch:
                            continue
                        f.write(ch)
                        bytes_done += len(ch)
                        pbar.update(len(ch))

            # success check
            if size_remote and bytes_done >= size_remote:
                partial.rename(final); pbar.close(); return final
            # or validate as ZIP if size unknown
            try:
                with zipfile.ZipFile(partial, "r") as z:
                    bad = z.testzip()
                if bad is None:
                    partial.rename(final); pbar.close(); return final
            except zipfile.BadZipFile:
                pass  # keep retrying

        except (requests.exceptions.SSLError,
                requests.exceptions.ChunkedEncodingError,
                requests.exceptions.ConnectionError,
                requests.exceptions.ReadTimeout) as e:
            # backoff then retry (resume continues via Range)
            time.sleep(sleep); sleep = min(sleep * 1.6, 10.0)
            continue

    pbar.close()
    raise RuntimeError(f"Failed to download {series_uid} after {max_retries} attempts. "
                       f"Partial file at: {partial} ({bytes_done} bytes)")

def extract_zip(zp: Path, to_dir: Path):
    with zipfile.ZipFile(zp, "r") as z:
        z.extractall(to_dir)

# ---- run on your pilot list ----
for uid in pilot["SeriesInstanceUID"]:
    sdir = OUT / uid
    zp = download_series_zip(uid, sdir)   # <- uses robust/resumable logic
    extract_zip(zp, sdir)

# Build a small manifest you can feed to your slice extractor
rows = []
for uid in pilot["SeriesInstanceUID"]:
    sdir = OUT / uid
    for p in sdir.rglob("*"):
        if p.is_file() and p.suffix.lower() != ".zip":
            rows.append({
                "file_path": str(p),
                "series_uid": uid,
                "modality": pilot.loc[pilot["SeriesInstanceUID"]==uid, "Modality"].iloc[0],
                "patient_id": (pilot.loc[pilot["SeriesInstanceUID"]==uid, "PatientID"].iloc[0]
                               if "PatientID" in pilot.columns else None),
                "collection": "CPTAC-CM",
            })
manifest = pd.DataFrame(rows).drop_duplicates("file_path")
manifest_path = OUT / "cptac_cm_pilot_manifest.csv"
manifest.to_csv(manifest_path, index=False)
print("Saved ", manifest_path)

Download one of the Stanford AIMI datasets MIDAS (parallel + resume-safe)¶

Goal. Given a full SAS URL to the MIDAS container, enumerate all blobs via the Azure Storage REST List API and download them in parallel to ./data/MRA-MIDAS, skipping any files you already have with the correct size.

What you need to provide¶

  • SAS_URL: paste the entire SAS container URL you copied from AIMI (includes sv, se, sp, sig, ).
    • Example pattern:
      https://<account>.blob.core.windows.net/<container>?sv=...&sr=c&sig=...&st=...&se=...&sp=rl

Security note: A SAS URL is a temporary credential. Treat it like a password. Do not commit it to version control or share it publicly.

How it works¶

  1. Parse the SAS URL

    • Split into:
      • BASE: https://account.blob.core.windows.net/container
      • SAS_QUERY: the query parameters (token fields), reused on every request.

  2. List all blobs (list_blobs)

    • Calls GET {BASE}?restype=container&comp=list&maxresults=5000&...SAS
    • Parses the XML response with xml.etree.ElementTree.
    • Follows server pagination via <NextMarker> until exhausted.
    • Returns a list of (name, size) for every blob in the container.

  3. Download each blob (download_one)

    • Builds the blob URL: f"{BASE}/{name}" + SAS_QUERY.
    • Resume-safe by size: if local file exists and its size matches, skip.
    • Streams to disk in 1 MiB chunks; verifies size on completion.

  4. Parallel downloads

    • Uses ThreadPoolExecutor(max_workers=8) (tune with MAX_WORKERS) to download blobs concurrently.
    • Progress bar via tqdm.

  5. Output

    • Files are saved under ./data/MRA-MIDAS/ mirroring blob paths.
    • Summary line: Done. Downloaded: X, skipped: Y.

Change these parameters if needed¶

  • DEST: local root directory (default ./data/MRA-MIDAS).
  • MAX_WORKERS: number of concurrent downloads (8 by default).
    Increase if you have fast network/IO; decrease on slower links or to be gentler to the server.

Typical workflow¶

  1. Paste your container-level SAS URL into SAS_URL.
  2. Run the cell:
    • Phase 1 prints: Remote blobs: N
    • Phase 2 shows a Downloading progress bar.
  3. On re-run, already-downloaded files are skipped (size check).

Troubleshooting¶

  • 403 (AuthorizationPermissionMismatch): SAS URL expired or lacks permission (sp must include l for list and r for read).
  • XML parse error: Ensure the SAS URL points to a container, not an individual blob.
  • Partial files: This script writes directly to final filenames (no partial extension). If you suspect an incomplete file, delete it and re-run; it will redownload.

#  paste the ENTIRE SAS URL you copied from AIMI
SAS_URL = "https://aimistanforddatasets01.blob.core.windows.net/midasmultimodalimagedatasetforaibasedskincancer?sv=2019-02-02&sr=c&sig=LlIiCoizhGn0MMrXEyd2qytftH5nm0JuVqyEeyzAASk%3D&st=2025-10-28T16%3A45%3A41Z&se=2025-11-27T16%3A50%3A41Z&sp=rl"  # REPLACE

DEST = Path("./data/MRA-MIDAS").resolve()
DEST.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
MAX_WORKERS = 8

# --- parse container base + query ---
u = urlparse(SAS_URL)
BASE = f"{u.scheme}://{u.netloc}{u.path}".rstrip("/")    # https://account.blob.core.windows.net/container
SAS_QUERY = dict(parse_qsl(u.query))                    # all SAS params (sv, se, sp, sig, etc.)

def list_blobs():
    """List all blobs in the container via REST (XML response), handling pagination."""
    blobs = []
    marker = None
    session = requests.Session()
    while True:
        params = {"restype": "container", "comp": "list", "maxresults": "5000", **SAS_QUERY}
        if marker: params["marker"] = marker
        r = session.get(BASE, params=params, timeout=60)
        r.raise_for_status()
        root = ET.fromstring(r.content)
        for b in root.findall(".//Blobs/Blob"):
            name = b.findtext("Name")
            size = int(b.findtext("Properties/Content-Length"))
            blobs.append((name, size))
        marker = root.findtext(".//NextMarker")
        if not marker: break
    return blobs

def download_one(name, size):
    """Download a single blob (resume-safe by size)."""
    dst = DEST / name
    dst.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    if dst.exists() and dst.stat().st_size == size:
        return True  # skipped
    # build file URL with SAS
    file_url = f"{BASE}/{name}"
    r = requests.get(file_url, params=SAS_QUERY, stream=True, timeout=120)
    r.raise_for_status()
    with open(dst, "wb") as f:
        for chunk in r.iter_content(2**20):
            if chunk: f.write(chunk)
    if dst.stat().st_size != size:
        dst.unlink(missing_ok=True)
        raise IOError(f"Size mismatch: {name}")
    return False  # downloaded

# 1) list
all_blobs = list_blobs()
print("Remote blobs:", len(all_blobs))

# 2) download in parallel
skipped = downloaded = 0
with ThreadPoolExecutor(max_workers=MAX_WORKERS) as ex, tqdm(total=len(all_blobs), desc="Downloading") as pbar:
    futs = {ex.submit(download_one, n, s): (n, s) for n, s in all_blobs}
    for fut in as_completed(futs):
        try:
            was_skipped = fut.result()
            skipped += int(was_skipped)
            downloaded += int(not was_skipped)
        except Exception as e:
            print("Error:", e)
        pbar.update(1)

print(f"Done. Downloaded: {downloaded}, skipped: {skipped}")

Build manifests and quicklook PNGs for MIDAS (photos) and CPTAC (DICOM) — post-download prep¶

Why this step?
After downloading the raw files, we need (1) a clean manifest for MIDAS photos with labels we can train on, and (2) a compact, visual PNG summary for each CPTAC DICOM series so we can browse/score without loading full DICOM stacks. Yesthis is exactly what you typically do right after data download.

A) MIDAS manifest from Excel + file system¶

Inputs

  • ./data/MRA-MIDAS/release_midas.xlsx (project metadata)
  • The MIDAS image directory (JPG/PNG files under ./data/MRA-MIDAS/**)

What the code does

  1. Column auto-detection: heuristically finds the image path column (e.g., file/image), diagnosis column (e.g., diagnosis/histopath), and lesion ID column.
  2. Binary label mapping: melanoma/malignant 1, everything else 0.
  3. Path resolution: for each Excel row, tries absolute path, relative path under the root, or a case-insensitive filename match if paths are inconsistent.
  4. Filtering & export: drops rows without a label and writes outputs/midas_manifest.csv with:
    • image_path, lesion_id, diagnosis_bin.

Why this helps

  • Gives a tidy, machine-readable table for training/embedding (image_path label).
  • Reports how many Excel rows didnt match any file so you can fix naming issues.

B) CPTAC PNG “thumbnails” + manifest from DICOMs¶

Inputs

  • ./data/tcia/CPTAC-CM_pilot/cptac_cm_pilot_manifest.csv (produced during download; has file_path, series_uid)

What the code does

  1. Group by series and sort files by InstanceNumber (fallback if missing).
  2. Pick representative slices (25/50/75% positions) per series.
  3. Read pixels robustly: pydicom with force=True.
  4. Modality-aware display:
    • CT windowing (center=40, width=400).
    • PT/MR/other z-score normalize to [0,1].
  5. Save quicklooks as PNG (3 slices per series) under ./data/tcia/CPTAC-CM_png/<series_uid>/slice_XX.png.
  6. Build a JSON manifest cptac_cm_png_manifest.json with:
    • series_uid, modality, body_part, series_desc, pngs (list of file paths), and a short human caption.

Why this helps

  • You can visualize and score series quickly without opening full DICOM volumes.
  • Downstream notebooks can load PNGs instantly for k-NN, CLIP mapping, and plots.

Practical notes¶

  • Robustness: DICOM reads use force=True and skip unreadable slices/series without failing the whole run.
  • Determinism: Slice selection is index-based (quartiles), producing stable thumbnails.
  • Performance: Only 3 PNGs per series keeps storage small but is usually enough for triage; adjust pick_indices if you want more.
  • Extensibility: Change CT window (center, width) or add modality-specific logic (e.g., MR sequences).

Outputs

  • outputs/midas_manifest.csv
  • data/tcia/CPTAC-CM_png/cptac_cm_png_manifest.json
  • data/tcia/CPTAC-CM_png/<series_uid>/slice_00.png, slice_01.png, slice_02.png

Conclusion:
Yesrunning this immediately after download is sensible. It standardizes paths/labels for MIDAS and creates lightweight visual surrogates + metadata for CPTAC, enabling fast EDA, scoring, and model experiments without heavy I/O.

def sort_by_instance(files):
    def instnum(p):
        try:
            ds = pydicom.dcmread(str(p), stop_before_pixels=True, force=True)
            return int(getattr(ds, "InstanceNumber", 1_000_000))
        except Exception:
            return 1_000_000
    return sorted(files, key=instnum)

def load_dcm_pixels(path):
    ds = pydicom.dcmread(str(path), force=True)
    arr = ds.pixel_array.astype(np.float32)
    slope = float(getattr(ds, "RescaleSlope", 1.0))
    inter = float(getattr(ds, "RescaleIntercept", 0.0))
    arr = arr * slope + inter
    return ds, arr

def window_ct(arr, center=40.0, width=400.0):
    lo, hi = center - width/2, center + width/2
    arr = np.clip(arr, lo, hi)
    return (arr - lo) / (hi - lo + 1e-6)

def norm_z(arr):
    m, s = float(np.mean(arr)), float(np.std(arr) + 1e-6)
    return (arr - m) / (3*s) + 0.5

def to_uint8(arr):
    return (np.clip(arr,0,1)*255.0).astype(np.uint8)

def pick_indices(n, k=3):
    if n<=k: return list(range(n))
    return [int(round(p*(n-1))) for p in (0.25, 0.5, 0.75)]

Build a robust MIDAS photo manifest from Excel + filesystem (name-mismatch tolerant)¶

Goal
Create outputs/midas_manifest.csv that maps each lesion/image to a resolved file path and a binary diagnosiseven when Excel paths are messy, relative, or renamed.

Inputs¶

  • Excel metadata: ./data/MRA-MIDAS/release_midas.xlsx
  • Expected columns (edit if your sheet uses different names):
    • midas_file_name image path or filename
    • midas_melanoma diagnosis field (0/1, True/False, Yes/No, or strings like melanoma/malignant)
    • midas_record_id lesion or record ID
  • Where to search for images (SEARCH_ROOTS): add folders if your images live elsewhere

What the code does¶

  1. Read Excel and define a robust diag_to_bin() to convert heterogeneous labels {0,1}.
  2. Index all images under SEARCH_ROOTS (recursive, JPG/PNG), building two fast lookup tables:
    • by_basename: case-insensitive exact filename match
    • by_stem: filename stem normalized to alphanumerics only (to tolerate spaces, dashes, suffixes)
  3. Resolve each Excel row to an actual file path via a cascade:
    • absolute path relative to MIDAS_ROOT exact basename match fuzzy stem match
  4. Assemble the manifest with columns:
    • image_path, lesion_id, diagnosis_bin
  5. Diagnostics report:
    • How many images were indexed vs. Excel rows
    • How many manifest rows were produced
    • Exact-name overlap and missing filenames (first few examples shown)
    • If zero rows, prints sample filenames it did find and suggests adding folders to SEARCH_ROOTS.

Output¶

  • Saved: outputs/midas_manifest.csv
  • Columns: image_path, lesion_id, diagnosis_bin

Tips & troubleshooting¶

  • If many Excel entries show as missing, add the true image root(s) to SEARCH_ROOTS.
  • The fuzzy stem matcher helps when Excel and disk differ by punctuation, case, or small suffixes.
  • Ensure the diagnosis column truly encodes melanoma/malignant vs. benign; adjust diag_to_bin() if needed.

def clip_img_embed(paths, bs=64):
    embs=[]

PNG_MANIFEST = Path("./data/tcia/CPTAC-CM_png/cptac_cm_png_manifest.json")
OUT = Path("./outputs"); OUT.mkdir(exist_ok=True)

# Load seriespngs list
cptac = pd.read_json(PNG_MANIFEST)
print("CPTAC series:", len(cptac))

# ResNet50 encoder (ImageNet weights as proxy)
DEVICE = "cuda" if torch.cuda.is_available() else "cpu"
model = timm.create_model("resnet50", pretrained=True, num_classes=0)  # 2048-D penultimate
model = model.eval().to(DEVICE)

# Preproc (timm standard)
tfm = transforms.Compose([
    transforms.Resize(256, interpolation=Image.BICUBIC),
    transforms.CenterCrop(224),
    transforms.ToTensor(),
    transforms.Normalize(
        mean=(0.485,0.456,0.406),
        std=(0.229,0.224,0.225)
    )
])

@torch.no_grad()
def embed_pngs(paths, bs=64):
    vecs=[]
    for i in range(0, len(paths), bs):
        ims=[]
        for p in paths[i:i+bs]:
            with Image.open(p).convert("RGB") as im:
                ims.append(tfm(im))
        xb = torch.stack(ims).to(DEVICE)
        z = model(xb)                    # [B, 2048]
        z = torch.nn.functional.normalize(z, dim=1)
        vecs.append(z.cpu())
    return torch.cat(vecs, 0).numpy()

series_ids, series_feat = [], []
for _, row in tqdm(cptac.iterrows(), total=len(cptac), desc="CPTAC series"):
    pngs = row["pngs"]
    if not pngs:
        continue
    V = embed_pngs(pngs, bs=64)          # [S, 2048] for S slices
    v = V.mean(0)                        # mean-pool to series-level
    v = v / (np.linalg.norm(v) + 1e-9)
    series_ids.append(row["series_uid"])
    series_feat.append(v)

Z_ct_2048 = np.stack(series_feat, 0)     # [N_series, 2048]
np.save(OUT/"cptac_resnet50_2048.npy", Z_ct_2048)
pd.Series(series_ids).to_csv(OUT/"cptac_series_ids.csv", index=False)
print("Saved:", Z_ct_2048.shape)

Map radiology features (ResNet50, 2048-D) into CLIP text space (512-D) with ridge regression¶
Goal

Align CPTAC radiology embeddings to CLIPs 512-D text space using captions from the PNG manifest, then save the projection matrix and mapped features.




Inputs¶
    

  • outputs/cptac_resnet50_2048.npy  radiology features Z_rad  ^{N2048}
    • 

  • data/tcia/CPTAC-CM_png/cptac_cm_png_manifest.json  per-series captions + PNG lists
    • 





Steps¶
    

  1. Load radiology embeddings
    

      

    • Z_rad has shape (N, 2048) from a ResNet50 (or similar) image encoder.
      • 

    

    2. 

  2. Rebuild the exact series order used for embeddings
    

      

    • Read the manifest, explode pngs, and group to count frames per series.
      • 

    • Keep only series with n_pngs > 0.
      • 

    • Merge back with the original JSON order to reproduce the same iteration order used when features were computed.
      • 

    • Assert that len(keep) == Z_rad.shape[0] to guarantee 1:1 alignment.
      • 

    

    3. 

  3. Create CLIP text embeddings from captions
    

      

    • Use open_clip with ViT-B/32 (openai) to encode each series caption.
      • 

    • L2-normalize to get Z_txt  ^{N512}.
      • 

    

    4. 

  4. Fit ridge regression to learn a linear map
    

      

    • Solve:  minW Z_radW  Z_txt + W, with =1.0, no intercept.
      • 

    • Result is W  ^{2048512}.
      • 

    

    5. 

  5. Project and normalize radiology features into CLIP space
    

      

    • Z_rad512 = normalize(Z_rad @ W)  (N, 512).
      • 

    • Save W and Z_rad512 for downstream retrieval/UMAP/diagnostics.
      • 

    • Also save the reconciled series_ids list for reproducibility.
      • 

    

    6. 





Outputs¶
    

  • outputs/W_ridge_2048_to_512.npy  projection matrix W (2048512)
    • 

  • outputs/cptac_clip_mapped_512.npy  mapped & L2-normalized features (N512)
    • 

  • outputs/cptac_series_ids_reconciled.csv  exact series order used
    • 





Notes & tips¶
    

  • The order check is criticalmisalignment between Z_rad rows and captions will corrupt the fit.
    • 

  • If you see shape/assert errors, rebuild Z_rad and the manifest with the same iteration order.
    • 

  • You can tune alpha to trade off fit vs. regularization; try 0.110.
    •

OUT = Path("./outputs")
MAN = Path("./data/tcia/CPTAC-CM_png/cptac_cm_png_manifest.json")

# --- Load radiology embeddings (N,2048) ---
Z_rad = np.load(OUT/"cptac_resnet50_2048.npy")  # shape (N,2048)

# --- Rebuild the exact series order used for Z_rad: keep rows with non-empty pngs ---
man = pd.read_json(MAN)
man = man.explode("pngs")                       # ensure pngs list is expanded to count properly
agg = (man.groupby("series_uid", as_index=False)
          .agg(caption=("caption","first"),
               n_pngs=("pngs","count")))
keep = agg.query("n_pngs > 0").reset_index(drop=True)

# Now 'keep' should match the order used when you iterated the manifest to embed
# If your embedding loop iterated the JSON order, sort by the original order:
orig = pd.read_json(MAN)[["series_uid","caption"]]  # original row order
orig = orig.drop_duplicates("series_uid", keep="first")
keep = orig.merge(keep, on=["series_uid","caption"], how="inner")

assert len(keep) == Z_rad.shape[0], f"After filtering, series {len(keep)} != features {Z_rad.shape[0]}"

series_ids = keep["series_uid"].tolist()
captions   = keep["caption"].fillna("melanoma patient | modality: unknown | body part: unknown").tolist()

# --- CLIP text embeddings to 512-D ---
DEVICE = "cuda" if torch.cuda.is_available() else "cpu"
clip_model, _, _ = open_clip.create_model_and_transforms("ViT-B-32", pretrained="openai", force_quick_gelu=True)
tokenizer = open_clip.get_tokenizer("ViT-B-32")
clip_model = clip_model.eval().to(DEVICE)

with torch.no_grad():
    toks = tokenizer(captions).to(DEVICE)
    Z_txt = clip_model.encode_text(toks).float()
    Z_txt = torch.nn.functional.normalize(Z_txt, dim=1).cpu().numpy()  # (N,512)

print("Shapes  Z_rad:", Z_rad.shape, "Z_txt:", Z_txt.shape)

# --- Ridge: map 2048 -> 512 ---
W = Ridge(alpha=1.0, fit_intercept=False).fit(Z_rad, Z_txt).coef_.T   # (2048,512)
np.save(OUT/"W_ridge_2048_to_512.npy", W)

Z_rad512 = (Z_rad @ W)
Z_rad512 /= (np.linalg.norm(Z_rad512, axis=1, keepdims=True) + 1e-9)
np.save(OUT/"cptac_clip_mapped_512.npy", Z_rad512)

# (Optional) save the reconciled order for future steps
pd.Series(series_ids).to_csv(OUT/"cptac_series_ids_reconciled.csv", index=False, header=False)

print("Saved:", OUT/"W_ridge_2048_to_512.npy", "|", OUT/"cptac_clip_mapped_512.npy")

Build a shared 128-D space for MIDAS (photos) and CPTAC (radiology)¶
Goal

Project MIDAS CLIP image embeddings and CPTAC radiology embeddings (already mapped to CLIP-512) into a shared 128-D space that preserves most variance (via PCA) and optionally injects simple supervision (2-D anchors from MIDAS labels).




Inputs¶
    

  • outputs/midas_clip_img_512.npy  MIDAS photo embeddings Z_photo512  ^{N_photo512}
    • 

  • outputs/midas_labels.npy  MIDAS binary labels y_midas  {0,1}^{N_photo}
    • 

  • outputs/cptac_clip_mapped_512.npy  CPTAC radiology embeddings already in CLIP space Z_rad512  ^{N_rad512}
    • 





Steps¶
    

  1. L2-normalize both datasets
    
Defensive normalization ensures stable PCA and cosine geometry.
    

    2. 

  2. Join and run PCA  126 dims
    
Concatenate MIDAS + CPTAC along the sample axis and fit PCA to 126 components, capturing most shared variance across the two sources.
    

    3. 

  3. Split back per dataset
    
Recover Zp_126 (photos) and Zr_126 (radiology) from the concatenated PCA output.
    

    4. 

  4. Add 2-D anchor features (optional supervision)
    

      

    • For MIDAS: append a 2-D one-hot (benign, malignant) derived from y_midas.  
      • 

    • For CPTAC: append zeros (unknown labels).
      
This yields a 128-D representation: 126 PCA dims + 2 anchor dims.
      • 

    

    5. 

  5. Save artifacts
    

      

    • outputs/midas_128.npy   Zp_128  ^{N_photo128}
      • 

    • outputs/cptac_128.npy  Zr_128  ^{N_rad128}
      • 

    

    6. 





Why this design?¶
    

  • PCA on the union enforces a common subspace driven by both domains.
    • 

  • 2-D anchors inject lightweight supervision from labeled photos, enabling downstream alignment/visualization (e.g., UMAP, k-NN bridging) without retraining encoders.
    • 





Output¶
The final print confirms shapes:

OUT = Path("./outputs"); OUT.mkdir(exist_ok=True)

# Load MIDAS (photo) CLIP 512-D + labels
Z_photo512 = np.load(OUT/"midas_clip_img_512.npy")           # (N_photo, 512)
y_midas     = np.load(OUT/"midas_labels.npy")                # (N_photo, )

# Load CPTAC (radiology) mapped to CLIP 512-D
Z_rad512   = np.load(OUT/"cptac_clip_mapped_512.npy")        # (N_rad, 512)

# L2-normalize defensively
def l2n(X):
    X = X.astype(np.float32, copy=False)
    n = np.linalg.norm(X, axis=1, keepdims=True) + 1e-9
    return X / n

Zp = l2n(Z_photo512)
Zr = l2n(Z_rad512)

# Stack for joint PCA
Z_union = np.vstack([Zp, Zr])                                # (N_photo+N_rad, 512)

# PCA to 126-D (we'll add 2-D anchor to make total 128)
pca = PCA(n_components=126, svd_solver="auto", random_state=0)
Z_union_126 = pca.fit_transform(Z_union)

# Split back
N_photo = Zp.shape[0]
Zp_126, Zr_126 = Z_union_126[:N_photo], Z_union_126[N_photo:]

# Optional supervised anchors (2-D one-hot for MIDAS labels; zeros for CPTAC)
anchor_photo = np.stack([ (y_midas==0).astype(np.float32),
                          (y_midas==1).astype(np.float32) ], axis=1)   # (N_photo, 2)
anchor_rad   = np.zeros((Zr_126.shape[0], 2), dtype=np.float32)

Zp_128 = np.hstack([Zp_126, anchor_photo])                   # (N_photo, 128)
Zr_128 = np.hstack([Zr_126, anchor_rad])                     # (N_rad,   128)

np.save(OUT/"midas_128.npy", Zp_128)
np.save(OUT/"cptac_128.npy", Zr_128)
print("Shapes:", Zp_128.shape, Zr_128.shape)

Fast UMAP visualization on the shared 128-D space¶
Goal

Create a quick 2-D UMAP plot for MIDAS photos and CPTAC radiology using a subset-fit + full-transform strategy for fast visualization on resource-constrained hardware.




What this cell does¶
    

  1. Limit BLAS threads (optional):
    
Sets OMP_NUM_THREADS / OPENBLAS_NUM_THREADS to avoid oversubscription on macOS laptops.
    

    2. 

  2. Prepare inputs:
    
Uses precomputed Zp_128 (MIDAS) and Zr_128 (CPTAC), each sample as a 128-D vector.
    

    3. 

  3. Subset-fit strategy:
    

      

    • Randomly sample up to 1,500 MIDAS points and all CPTAC points to fit UMAP.  
      • 

    • Then transform the entire MIDAS and CPTAC sets using the fitted UMAP model.
      
This preserves structure while cutting runtime dramatically.
      • 

    

    4. 

  4. UMAP settings (speed-oriented):
    

      

    • n_neighbors=15 (smaller, faster)  
      • 

    • min_dist=0.3 (looser packing, fewer epochs needed)  
      • 

    • n_epochs=100 (reduced from ~200)  
      • 

    • init="random" (faster than spectral)  
      • 

    • metric="cosine" (good for normalized embeddings)  
      • 

    • low_memory=True, force_approximation_algorithm=True (NNDescent)  
      • 

    • random_state=0 for reproducibility
      • 

    

    5. 

  5. Plot:
    
Scatter the 2-D embeddings with distinct colors for MIDAS vs CPTAC.
    

    6. 





Output¶
A 2-D UMAP figure titled UMAP (fast) on shared 128-D space showing the relative placement of MIDAS and CPTAC embeddings.


Tip: If you want slightly more detail at the expense of speed, increase n_neighbors (e.g., 30) or n_epochs (e.g., 200).

Evaluation: Cross-repo KNN retrieval + simple classifier¶
Goal

1) Retrieve nearest CPTAC radiology series for MIDAS derm photos in a shared 128-D space;

2) Train a simple MIDAS-only classifier and score CPTAC to see modality/body-part patterns.




Prerequisites¶
Saved by earlier steps:


    

  • outputs/midas_clip_img_512.npy, outputs/midas_labels.npy
    • 

  • data/tcia/CPTAC-CM_png/cptac_cm_png_manifest.json
    • 

  • outputs/cptac_clip_mapped_512.npy (from the 2048512 ridge mapping)
    • 





Load & sanity checks¶
    

  • Read MIDAS manifest + CLIP (512-D) and labels, CPTAC JSON manifest, and CPTAC CLIP-mapped (512-D).
    • 

  • Assert equal counts between embeddings and their manifests.
    • 

  • L2-normalize both embeddings for stable cosine geometry.
    • 





Shared PCA → 128-D¶
    

  • Fit a single PCA (n=128) on the stacked 512-D features ([MIDAS ; CPTAC]) to make a shared space.
    • 

  • Transform each domain  Zp_128 (MIDAS) and Zr_128 (CPTAC).
    • 

  • Save both to outputs/midas_128.npy and outputs/cptac_128.npy.
    • 





A) Cross-repo KNN retrieval (MIDAS → CPTAC)¶
    

  • Build a NearestNeighbors index on CPTAC (Zr_128) with cosine distance.
    • 

  • Sample up to 50 random MIDAS queries and retrieve top-5 CPTAC neighbors.
    • 

  • Emit a tidy CSV outputs/knn_midas_to_cptac_top5.csv with:
      

    • MIDAS image path + binary label,
      • 

    • matched CPTAC series_uid, modality/description/caption (if present),
      • 

    • cosine distances and ranks.
      • 

    

    • 

  • (Optional) You can visually inspect a few query rows or render thumbnails later.
    • 





B) Simple classifier: Train on MIDAS → Score CPTAC¶
    

  1. 5-fold AUROC on MIDAS
    

      

    • LogisticRegression (lbfgs, class_weight='balanced', max_iter=1000), stratified 5-fold.  
      • 

    • Report mean AUROC and per-fold scores.
      • 

    

    2. 

  2. Fit on full MIDAS
    

      

    • Train LR on all Zp_128 and labels y.
      • 

    

    3. 

  3. Score CPTAC
    

      

    • Predict melanoma probability on Zr_128; attach to CPTAC dataframe as pred_score.  
      • 

    • Save to outputs/cptac_scored_by_midas_lr.csv.
      • 

    

    4. 

  4. Quick plots & table
    

      

    • Plot score distributions by modality (density histograms).  
      • 

    • Show a small top-K table of highest-scoring CPTAC series for qualitative review.
      • 

    

    5. 





Outputs¶
    

  • outputs/midas_128.npy, outputs/cptac_128.npy  
    • 

  • outputs/knn_midas_to_cptac_top5.csv  
    • 

  • outputs/cptac_scored_by_midas_lr.csv  
    • 

  • Console printouts: shapes, AUROC summary; histogram figure; top-K table display.
    • 





Notes & Tips¶
    

  • Cosine distance assumes L2-normalized rowsthis cell normalizes defensively.
    • 

  • For reproducibility, a fixed SEED=0 is used in PCA and random sampling.
    • 

  • You can tune n_neighbors, the number of sampled queries, and LR hyperparams to balance speed vs. fidelity.
    •

# === Evaluation: KNN retrieval + simple classifier ===
# Prereqs saved by earlier steps:
#   outputs/midas_clip_img_512.npy, outputs/midas_labels.npy
#   data/tcia/CPTAC-CM_png/cptac_cm_png_manifest.json
#   (optional) outputs/cptac_clip_mapped_512.npy
#
# If you don't have cptac_clip_mapped_512.npy yet, make sure you ran the ridge-mapping step.

# -------- paths --------
OUT         = Path("./outputs"); OUT.mkdir(exist_ok=True)
MIDAS_CSV   = Path("./outputs/midas_manifest.csv")
MIDAS_EMB   = Path("./outputs/midas_clip_img_512.npy")
MIDAS_Y     = Path("./outputs/midas_labels.npy")
CPTAC_JSON  = Path("./data/tcia/CPTAC-CM_png/cptac_cm_png_manifest.json")
CPTAC_EMB   = Path("./outputs/cptac_clip_mapped_512.npy")  # from ridge map (2048->512)
SEED        = 0

# -------- load data --------
midas_df = pd.read_csv(MIDAS_CSV)
Zp_512   = np.load(MIDAS_EMB)         # (N_midas, 512)
y        = np.load(MIDAS_Y)           # (N_midas,)
cptac    = pd.read_json(CPTAC_JSON)   # columns: series_uid, modality, body_part, series_desc, pngs, caption
Zr_512   = np.load(CPTAC_EMB)         # (N_cptac, 512)

# safety checks
assert Zp_512.shape[0] == len(midas_df), "Mismatch MIDAS embeddings vs manifest"
assert Zr_512.shape[0] == len(cptac), "Mismatch CPTAC embeddings vs manifest"

# L2 normalize (should already be, but safe)
Zp_512 = Zp_512 / (np.linalg.norm(Zp_512, axis=1, keepdims=True)+1e-9)
Zr_512 = Zr_512 / (np.linalg.norm(Zr_512, axis=1, keepdims=True)+1e-9)

# -------- Shared PCA to 128-D (as in plan) --------
np.random.seed(SEED)
pca = PCA(n_components=128, random_state=SEED)
Z_all_512 = np.vstack([Zp_512, Zr_512])
pca.fit(Z_all_512)

Zp_128 = pca.transform(Zp_512).astype(np.float32)
Zr_128 = pca.transform(Zr_512).astype(np.float32)

np.save(OUT/"midas_128.npy", Zp_128)
np.save(OUT/"cptac_128.npy", Zr_128)

print("Shapes ", "Zp_128:", Zp_128.shape, "Zr_128:", Zr_128.shape)

# =========================================================
# A) Cross-repo KNN retrieval (MIDAS -> CPTAC)
# =========================================================
# Use cosine distance in 128-D
knn = NearestNeighbors(
    n_neighbors=5, metric="cosine", algorithm="auto", n_jobs=-1
).fit(Zr_128)

# pick a small random sample of MIDAS queries for display (adjust as you like)
rng = np.random.default_rng(SEED)
q_idx = rng.choice(Zp_128.shape[0], size=min(50, Zp_128.shape[0]), replace=False)

dist, idx = knn.kneighbors(Zp_128[q_idx])
# Build a tidy table with MIDAS query  top-5 CPTAC matches
rows = []
for qi, (drow, irow) in enumerate(zip(dist, idx)):
    mrow = midas_df.iloc[q_idx[qi]]
    for rank, (dj, ij) in enumerate(zip(drow, irow), start=1):
        crow = cptac.iloc[ij]
        rows.append({
            "midas_image": mrow["image_path"],
            "midas_label": int(mrow["diagnosis_bin"]),
            "cptac_series_uid": crow["series_uid"],
            "cptac_modality": crow.get("modality", ""),
            "cptac_desc": crow.get("series_desc", ""),
            "cptac_caption": crow.get("caption", ""),
            "distance_cosine": float(dj),
            "rank": rank
        })

retrieval_df = pd.DataFrame(rows)
retrieval_csv = OUT/"knn_midas_to_cptac_top5.csv"
retrieval_df.to_csv(retrieval_csv, index=False)
print(" Saved retrieval table ", retrieval_csv)
display(retrieval_df.head(10))

# (Optional) quick qualitative peek: show a few MIDAS thumbnails and list top matches
# Note: rendering lots of images in Jupyter can be slow; we keep this textual by default.


# =========================================================
# B) Simple classifier trained on MIDAS  score CPTAC
# =========================================================
# 1) Cross-validated AUROC on MIDAS, then 2) fit on full MIDAS, 3) score CPTAC and plot by modality.

def cv_auroc_lr(X, y, seed=SEED):
    skf = StratifiedKFold(n_splits=5, shuffle=True, random_state=seed)
    aucs = []
    for tr, te in skf.split(X, y):
        clf = LogisticRegression(
            max_iter=1000,
            class_weight="balanced",
            solver="lbfgs",
            n_jobs=-1
        )
        clf.fit(X[tr], y[tr])
        p = clf.predict_proba(X[te])[:, 1]
        aucs.append(roc_auc_score(y[te], p))
    return float(np.mean(aucs)), [float(a) for a in aucs]

mid_auc, fold_aucs = cv_auroc_lr(Zp_128, y)
print(f"MIDAS 5-fold AUROC (mean): {mid_auc:.3f} | folds:", np.round(fold_aucs, 3))

# Fit on all MIDAS
clf_full = LogisticRegression(
    max_iter=1000, class_weight="balanced", solver="lbfgs", n_jobs=-1
).fit(Zp_128, y)

# Score CPTAC
cptac_scores = clf_full.predict_proba(Zr_128)[:, 1]
cptac_scored = cptac.copy()
cptac_scored["pred_score"] = cptac_scores

# Save scored table
scored_csv = OUT/"cptac_scored_by_midas_lr.csv"
cptac_scored.to_csv(scored_csv, index=False)
print(" Saved CPTAC scores ", scored_csv)

# Plot score distributions by modality (quick look)
plt.figure(figsize=(6.5, 4.5))
for mod in sorted(cptac_scored["modality"].fillna("NA").unique()):
    m = (cptac_scored["modality"].fillna("NA") == mod)
    if m.sum() == 0:
        continue
    plt.hist(cptac_scored.loc[m, "pred_score"], bins=20, alpha=0.5, label=f"{mod} (n={m.sum()})", density=True)
plt.xlabel("Predicted melanoma probability (from MIDAS-trained LR)")
plt.ylabel("Density")
plt.title("CPTAC score distributions by modality")
plt.legend()
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# Also dump a small top-K table for quick inspection
topk = cptac_scored.sort_values("pred_score", ascending=False).head(15)
display(topk[["series_uid","modality","body_part","series_desc","pred_score"]])

Qualitative retrieval panels: MIDAS query vs. top-K CPTAC matches¶
Purpose

Visually inspect cross-repository retrieval quality by showing one MIDAS derm photo (query) on the left and its top-K CPTAC radiology matches on the right, using the precomputed KNN results.


Inputs


    

  • ./outputs/midas_manifest.csv  MIDAS images + labels.
    • 

  • ./data/tcia/CPTAC-CM_png/cptac_cm_png_manifest.json  CPTAC series with PNG thumbnails and captions.
    • 

  • ./outputs/knn_midas_to_cptac_top5.csv  KNN table with midas_image, midas_label, cptac_series_uid, cptac_modality, series_desc, distance_cosine, rank.
    • 



Key function: show_panel(query_row, k=5, figsize=(12,3.2))


    

  • Takes one row (typically rank==1) from the retrieval table to pick a single MIDAS query image.
    • 

  • Collects the top-K CPTAC neighbors for that same midas_image.
    • 

  • Renders a 1(K+1) figure:
      

    • Column 1: the MIDAS query image with its binary label.
      • 

    • Columns 2..K+1: the first PNG thumbnail from each matched CPTAC series, titled with modality and cosine distance (d=...) and labeled by a short series description.
      • 

    

    • 



Workflow


    

  1. Load the three data sources (MIDAS CSV, CPTAC JSON, KNN CSV).
    2. 

  2. Filter the KNN table to rank==1 to get one entry per MIDAS query.
    3. 

  3. For a few random queries, call show_panel(row, k=5) to visualize the query and its top-5 matches.
    4. 

  4. Use plt.show() to display each panel inline.
    5. 



What to look for


    

  • Are high-scoring matches (small cosine distance) semantically reasonable given the MIDAS query?
    • 

  • Any modality/body-part patterns in the retrieved CPTAC series?
    • 

  • Outliers with unexpectedly large distances or missing thumbnails.
    • 



Notes


    

  • The function uses only the first PNG per CPTAC series for speed; extend to multiple slices if desired.
    • 

  • Ensure the pngs paths exist on disk; otherwise, a panel cell will render blank.
    • 

  • You can sort or filter retr by distance_cosine or modality to target specific cases.
    • 














In [4]:



    


OUT         = Path("./outputs")
MIDAS_CSV   = OUT/"midas_manifest.csv"
CPTAC_JSON  = Path("./data/tcia/CPTAC-CM_png/cptac_cm_png_manifest.json")
RETR_CSV    = OUT/"knn_midas_to_cptac_top5.csv"

midas_df = pd.read_csv(MIDAS_CSV)
cptac    = pd.read_json(CPTAC_JSON)
retr     = pd.read_csv(RETR_CSV)

def show_panel(query_row, k=5, figsize=(12,3.2)):
    """
    query_row: a single row from retrieval_df (rank==1 recommended to pick the MIDAS image);
               we'll collect its top-k rows by midas_image.
    """
    qimg = query_row["midas_image"]
    subset = retr[retr["midas_image"]==qimg].sort_values("rank").head(k)
    # build figure: 1 row, k+1 columns (left = MIDAS, right = k CPTAC)
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, k+1, figsize=figsize)
    # MIDAS query
    im = Image.open(qimg).convert("RGB")
    axes[0].imshow(im); axes[0].set_title(f"MIDAS (label={query_row['midas_label']})", fontsize=10)
    axes[0].axis("off")
    # CPTAC matches
    for j, (_, r) in enumerate(subset.iterrows(), start=1):
        # first PNG for that CPTAC series
        srow = cptac[cptac["series_uid"]==r["cptac_series_uid"]].iloc[0]
        pngs = srow["pngs"]
        pth  = pngs[0] if isinstance(pngs, list) and len(pngs) else None
        if pth and Path(pth).exists():
            im = Image.open(pth).convert("RGB")
            axes[j].imshow(im)
        axes[j].set_title(f"{r['cptac_modality']}  d={r['distance_cosine']:.3f}", fontsize=9)
        axes[j].set_xlabel(srow.get("series_desc","")[:22], fontsize=8)
        axes[j].axis("off")
    plt.tight_layout()
    return fig

# demo a few random queries
cand = retr[retr["rank"]==1].copy()
for _ in range(3):  # show 3 panels
    row = cand.sample(1, random_state=np.random.randint(0, 99999)).iloc[0]
    show_panel(row, k=5)
    plt.show()



    















    

















    

















    




























Quick sanity check: Top-1 retrieval distance summary¶
Goal

Summarize the cosine distance of the top-1 CPTAC neighbor for each MIDAS query from the KNN results. Lower distance  closer match.


Inputs


    

  • ./outputs/knn_midas_to_cptac_top5.csv  table with columns like rank and distance_cosine.
    • 



What the cell does


    

  1. Loads the KNN table into a DataFrame.
    2. 

  2. Filters to rank == 1 (the nearest neighbor per query).
    3. 

  3. Prints the median, minimum, and maximum cosine distances across all top-1 matches.
    4. 



How to read it


    

  • Distances range from 0 (identical direction) to 2 for cosine distance if defined as 1 - cosine_similarity (common range is 02; many pipelines stay in 01).  
    • 

  • Smaller values indicate better alignment between the MIDAS image embedding and its best CPTAC match.
    • 



Notes


    

  • If you observe large medians (e.g., > ~0.8 with cosine distance), consider improving the shared embedding space (e.g., better text prompts, different mapping, or normalization).
    • 

  • You can also compare this summary against a random baseline to verify that retrieval is better than chance.
    •

      top1['distance_cosine'].median(),
      top1['distance_cosine'].min(),
      top1['distance_cosine'].max())

Train & evaluate a simple classifier on MIDAS (128-D)¶
Goal

Evaluate how well the 128-D MIDAS embeddings (Z_photo_128.npy) separate melanoma vs non-melanoma, using a lightweight logistic-regression baseline.


Inputs


    

  • outputs/Z_photo_128.npy  MIDAS embeddings of shape (N_photo, 128)  
    • 

  • outputs/midas_labels.npy  binary labels (N_photo,)
    • 



Procedure


    

  1. Report dataset shapes and positive rate for a quick sanity check.  
    2. 

  2. Perform 5-fold Stratified CV with LogisticRegression (LBFGS, max_iter=500) and compute AUROC per fold.  
    3. 

  3. Print mean  std AUROC and per-fold scores.  
    4. 

  4. Fit the final classifier on all MIDAS data.  
    5. 

  5. Persist the trained model to outputs/midas_logreg_128.joblib (via joblib.dump) for reuse.
    6. 



Notes


    

  • Stratification preserves label balance across folds.  
    • 

  • AUROC is threshold-free and robust for imbalanced datasets; consider tracking PR-AUC too if positives are rare.  
    •

Fast top-5 retrieval via cosine similarity (vectorized)¶
What it does

Computes top-5 CPTAC matches for each MIDAS image using cosine similarity in the shared 128-D space.


Steps


    

  1. L2-normalize both matrices so dot products equal cosine similarity.
    2. 

  2. Compute the full similarity matrix S = Z_photo  Z_rad^T.
    3. 

  3. Use argpartition to get top-k indices per row, then sort those k by exact similarity.
    4. 

  4. Build a tidy table with photo_idx, series_idx, rank, sim, and distance_cosine = 1  sim.
    5. 



Inputs


    

  • outputs/Z_photo_128.npy (N_photo  128)  
    • 

  • outputs/Z_rad_128.npy (N_series  128)
    • 



Output


    

  • outputs/knn_midas_to_cptac_top5.csv  top-5 nearest CPTAC series per MIDAS image.
    • 














In [11]:



    


# Fast cosine top-5 using matrix multiply on L2-normalized rows
def l2n(a, eps=1e-9):
    n = np.linalg.norm(a, axis=1, keepdims=True); n[n<eps] = eps
    return a / n

Zp_n = l2n(np.load("./outputs/Z_photo_128.npy"))
Zr_n = l2n(np.load("./outputs/Z_rad_128.npy"))

S = Zp_n @ Zr_n.T                         # cosine similarity (N_photo x N_series)
topk = 5
idx = np.argpartition(-S, kth=topk-1, axis=1)[:,:topk]
# exact sort within the topk
rows = []
for i in range(S.shape[0]):
    pairs = sorted([(j, S[i,j]) for j in idx[i]], key=lambda x: -x[1])
    for rank,(j,sim) in enumerate(pairs, start=1):
        rows.append({"photo_idx": i, "series_idx": j, "rank": rank, "sim": float(sim), "distance_cosine": float(1.0-sim)})
knn = pd.DataFrame(rows)
knn.to_csv("./outputs/knn_midas_to_cptac_top5.csv", index=False)
print("Saved  ./outputs/knn_midas_to_cptac_top5.csv")

Summarize CPTAC scores by modality and body part¶
Goal

Compute descriptive statistics of the CPTAC melanoma-likeness scores, grouped by modality and by body part.


What the code does


    

  • Loads ./outputs/cptac_scored.csv (must contain: series_uid, modality, body_part, score).
    • 

  • For each group:
      

    • Calculates median and IQR (p25, p75).
      • 

    • Estimates a 95% bootstrap CI for the median (5,000 resamples, fixed RNG for reproducibility).
      • 

    

    • 

  • Prints two tables:
1) Summary by modality
    
2) Summary by body part (top 8 rows by median)
    • 



Why bootstrap?

The sampling distribution of the median can be non-normal; bootstrap gives a simple, assumption-light CI.


Output

Two neatly sorted DataFrames with columns:

[group, n, median, p25, p75, ci2.5, ci97.5].













In [13]:



    


scores = pd.read_csv("./outputs/cptac_scored.csv")  # columns: series_uid, modality, body_part, score
def summary(df, by):
    out = []
    for name, g in df.groupby(by):
        s = g["score"].to_numpy()
        m = np.median(s); lo, hi = np.percentile(s, [25, 75])
        # bootstrap 95% CI for median
        bs = np.median(np.random.default_rng(0).choice(s, (5000, len(s)), replace=True), axis=1)
        ci = np.percentile(bs, [2.5, 97.5])
        out.append((name, len(s), m, lo, hi, ci[0], ci[1]))
    return pd.DataFrame(out, columns=[by, "n", "median", "p25", "p75", "ci2.5", "ci97.5"]).sort_values("median", ascending=False)

print("By modality:\n", summary(scores, "modality"), "\n")
print("By body_part (top 8):\n", summary(scores, "body_part").head(8))

# --- CPTAC PNG browser with smarter titles & compact grid --------------------

# --- inputs (re-use your existing DataFrames if already in memory) ---
MAN_PATH    = "./data/tcia/CPTAC-CM_png/cptac_cm_png_manifest.json"
SCORES_PATH = "./outputs/cptac_scores.csv"   # fallback if `scores` not in memory

man = pd.read_json(MAN_PATH)

# 1) Fill missing body_part from series/study description (nice for MR)
def infer_body_part_row(row):
    bp = (row.get("body_part") or "").strip()
    if bp:
        return bp
    sdesc = (row.get("series_desc") or "").upper()
    # try common tags
    tags = [
        "BRAIN","HEAD","NECK","CHEST","ABDOMEN","PELVIS",
        "CHEST_TO_PELVIS","CHEST TO PELVIS","WHOLEBODY","WHOLE BODY","WB"
    ]
    for t in tags:
        if t in sdesc:
            return t.replace(" ","_")
    return "UNK"

if "body_part" not in man.columns:
    man["body_part"] = "UNK"
man["body_part"] = man.apply(infer_body_part_row, axis=1)

# ensure png list column is always a list (and filtered to existing files)
def normalize_pngs(xs):
    xs = xs if isinstance(xs, (list, tuple)) else []
    return [p for p in xs if isinstance(p, str) and os.path.exists(p)]
man["pngs"] = man["pngs"].apply(normalize_pngs)

# load/align scores
try:
    scores  # if already in memory, leave it
except NameError:
    scores = pd.read_csv(SCORES_PATH)

# if modality/body_part missing in scores, merge them from manifest
if not {"modality","body_part"}.issubset(scores.columns):
    scores = scores.merge(
        man[["series_uid","modality","body_part"]],
        on="series_uid", how="left"
    )

# convenience lookups
score_map = dict(zip(scores.series_uid, scores.score))
mod_map   = dict(zip(scores.series_uid, scores.modality))
body_map  = dict(zip(scores.series_uid, scores.body_part))

def uid_tail(uid, n=6):
    return uid.split(".")[-1][:n]

def get_pngs(uid):
    r = man.loc[man.series_uid == uid]
    if r.empty:
        return []
    return r.iloc[0]["pngs"]

def show(series_ids, title, max_cols=5):
    """Compact grid (no blank columns), robust to rows with <max_cols PNGs."""
    # resolve & cap each rows png list; compute actual number of columns
    png_lists, ncols = [], 0
    for uid in series_ids:
        pngs = get_pngs(uid)
        pngs = pngs[:max_cols] if isinstance(pngs, list) else []
        png_lists.append(pngs)
        ncols = max(ncols, len(pngs))
    if ncols == 0:
        print(f"[WARN] No PNGs found for: {series_ids}")
        return

    nrows = len(series_ids)
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(nrows, ncols, figsize=(3.2*ncols, 2.6*nrows))
    if nrows == 1 and ncols == 1:
        axes = np.array([[axes]])
    elif nrows == 1:
        axes = axes[None, :]
    elif ncols == 1:
        axes = axes[:, None]

    for i, uid in enumerate(series_ids):
        row_pngs = png_lists[i]
        for j in range(ncols):
            ax = axes[i, j]
            if j < len(row_pngs):
                img = plt.imread(row_pngs[j])
                ax.imshow(img, cmap="gray")
                ax.axis("off")
                if j == 0:
                    s   = score_map.get(uid, float("nan"))
                    mod = (mod_map.get(uid, "") or "?")
                    bp  = (body_map.get(uid, "") or "")
                    ax.set_title(f"{mod}  {s:.3f}\n{bp}  {uid_tail(uid)}", fontsize=10)
            else:
                ax.axis("off")

    plt.suptitle(title, y=1.02, fontsize=12)
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

# --- choose the series to display (top/bottom by score) ---
top = scores.sort_values("score", ascending=False).head(5)["series_uid"].tolist()
bot = scores.sort_values("score", ascending=True ).head(5)["series_uid"].tolist()

show(top, "Top-scored CPTAC series",   max_cols=5)
show(bot, "Bottom-scored CPTAC series", max_cols=5)

# (Optional) show best-per-modality by z-score within modality
if "modality" in scores.columns:
    scores["z_in_mod"] = scores.groupby("modality")["score"].transform(
        lambda x: (x - x.mean()) / (x.std(ddof=1) + 1e-9)
    )
    top_by_mod = (
        scores.sort_values(["modality", "z_in_mod"], ascending=[True, False])
              .groupby("modality")
              .head(3)["series_uid"].tolist()
    )
    show(top_by_mod, "Top z-score within each modality", max_cols=5)



    















    

















    

















    




























Train → Calibrate → Apply: MIDAS → CPTAC melanoma scoring¶
Purpose

1) Train and cross-validate a calibrated logistic-regression classifier on MIDAS CLIP-512 embeddings.

2) Fit a final calibrated model on all MIDAS data.

3) Apply it to CPTAC radiology embeddings (already mapped into CLIP-512) and summarize results.




1) MIDAS classifier with calibrated probabilities¶
    

  • Data:  
      

    • outputs/midas_clip_img_512.npy  image embeddings (N_photo, 512)  
      • 

    • outputs/midas_labels.npy  binary labels (N_photo,)
      • 

    

    • 

  • Modeling:
      

    • Pipeline: StandardScaler  LogisticRegression(C=1.0, lbfgs, class_weight='balanced', max_iter=2000).  
      • 

    • 5-fold Stratified CV: compute AUROC and PR-AUC on held-out folds.  
      • 

    • Probability calibration: CalibratedClassifierCV(..., method='sigmoid') wraps the pipeline to correct probability scale; CV=3 within each training fold.  
      • 

    • Report mean  std for AUROC and PR-AUC; store out-of-fold probabilities for sanity checks.
      • 

    

    • 

  • Final model:
      

    • Refit the same pipeline on all MIDAS data with CV=5 calibration.  
      • 

    • Save to outputs/midas_calibrated_lr.joblib.
      • 

    

    • 



Why calibration?

Logistic regression often produces well-behaved scores, but domain shift and regularization can still mis-scale probabilities. Platt (sigmoid) calibration improves interpretability of the 01 scores.




2) Score CPTAC with the calibrated MIDAS model¶
    

  • Input: outputs/cptac_clip_mapped_512.npy  CPTAC radiology features (N_series, 512) after 2048512 mapping.  
    • 

  • Metadata: read ./outputs/cptac_scored.csv (contains at least series_uid, modality, body_part; the new score column will be appended).  
    • 

  • Action: predict_proba to obtain melanoma-likeness  [0,1]; save to outputs/cptac_scores_calibrated.csv.
    • 





3) Cohort summaries & basic statistical check¶
    

  • Bootstrap summaries:
      

    • Function summarize(key) groups by modality or body_part and reports:
        

      • n, median, p25, p75, and bootstrap 95% CI for the mean via resampling (bs_ci).
        • 

      

      • 

    • Print ranked tables for modality, and top-K body parts (e.g., 8 most frequent).
      • 

    

    • 

  • Non-parametric comparison (optional):
      

    • MannWhitney U test (two-sided) between CT and MR score distributions if both are present; prints p and sample sizes.
      • 

    

    • 





Outputs¶
    

  • Metrics:  
      

    •  MIDAS 5-fold AUROC:   
      • 

    •  MIDAS 5-fold PR-AUC: 
      • 

    

    • 

  • Artifacts:  
      

    • outputs/midas_calibrated_lr.joblib (final calibrated classifier)  
      • 

    • outputs/cptac_scores_calibrated.csv (CPTAC series with calibrated scores)
      • 

    

    • 

  • Tables (printed): per-modality and per-body-part summaries, plus optional CT vs MR MannWhitney p-value.
    • 



Notes


    

  • class_weight='balanced' mitigates label imbalance in MIDAS.  
    • 

  • Standardization improves LR convergence and stability across folds.  
    • 

  • If SciPy is unavailable, the MannWhitney step is skipped gracefully.
    •

# --- 1) Train & validate a MIDAS melanoma classifier -------------------------
rng = np.random.default_rng(0)

OUT = Path("./outputs"); OUT.mkdir(exist_ok=True)

Zp = np.load(OUT/"midas_clip_img_512.npy")          # (N_photo, 512)
y  = np.load(OUT/"midas_labels.npy").astype(int)    # (N_photo,)

# Stratified 5-fold CV for AUROC/PR-AUC
skf = StratifiedKFold(n_splits=5, shuffle=True, random_state=42)
cv_aucs, cv_prs = [], []
oof = np.zeros(len(y), dtype=float)

for tr, te in skf.split(Zp, y):
    pipe = make_pipeline(
        StandardScaler(with_mean=True, with_std=True),
        LogisticRegression(
            penalty="l2", C=1.0, max_iter=2000, solver="lbfgs",
            class_weight="balanced", random_state=0
        )
    )
    # calibrate sigmoid on held-out fold
    cal = CalibratedClassifierCV(pipe, cv=3, method="sigmoid")
    cal.fit(Zp[tr], y[tr])
    p = cal.predict_proba(Zp[te])[:,1]
    oof[te] = p
    cv_aucs.append(roc_auc_score(y[te], p))
    cv_prs.append(average_precision_score(y[te], p))

print(f" MIDAS 5-fold AUROC: {np.mean(cv_aucs):.3f}  {np.std(cv_aucs):.3f}")
print(f" MIDAS 5-fold PR-AUC: {np.mean(cv_prs):.3f}  {np.std(cv_prs):.3f}")

# Train final calibrated model on all MIDAS data
final_pipe = make_pipeline(
    StandardScaler(with_mean=True, with_std=True),
    LogisticRegression(
        penalty="l2", C=1.0, max_iter=2000, solver="lbfgs",
        class_weight="balanced", random_state=0
    )
)
final_model = CalibratedClassifierCV(final_pipe, cv=5, method="sigmoid")
final_model.fit(Zp, y)

# Save final model with joblib
joblib.dump(final_model, OUT/"midas_calibrated_lr.joblib")

# --- 2) Score CPTAC with the calibrated model --------------------------------
# Inputs we produced earlier
Zr_512 = np.load(OUT/"cptac_clip_mapped_512.npy")   # (N_series, 512) mapped radiology features
scores_df = pd.read_csv("./outputs/cptac_scored.csv")  # has at least series_uid, modality, body_part
# (if you don't have it, you can reconstruct metadata by reading the JSON manifest)

p_cptac = final_model.predict_proba(Zr_512)[:,1]    # melanoma-likeness 0..1
scores_df["score"] = p_cptac
scores_df.to_csv(OUT/"cptac_scores_calibrated.csv", index=False)
print(" Saved calibrated CPTAC scores ", OUT/"cptac_scores_calibrated.csv")

# --- 3) Summary tables + simple tests ----------------------------------------
def bs_ci(x, n=2000, alpha=0.05):
    xs = np.array([rng.choice(x, size=len(x), replace=True).mean() for _ in range(n)])
    return np.quantile(xs, [alpha/2, 1-alpha/2])

def summarize(group_key, top_k=None):
    g = scores_df.copy()
    if top_k:
        # optional: keep only frequent groups
        vc = g[group_key].value_counts().head(top_k).index
        g = g[g[group_key].isin(vc)]
    out = (
        g.groupby(group_key)["score"]
         .agg(n="count", median="median", p25=lambda x: np.quantile(x,0.25), p75=lambda x: np.quantile(x,0.75))
         .reset_index()
    )
    ci_lo, ci_hi = [], []
    for _, row in out.iterrows():
        vals = g.loc[g[group_key]==row[group_key], "score"].to_numpy()
        lo, hi = bs_ci(vals)
        ci_lo.append(lo); ci_hi.append(hi)
    out["ci2.5"] = ci_lo; out["ci97.5"] = ci_hi
    return out.sort_values("median", ascending=False)

print("\nBy modality:")
print(summarize("modality").to_string(index=False))

print("\nBy body_part (top 8):")
print(summarize("body_part", top_k=8).to_string(index=False))

# Optional: a quick non-parametric test CT vs MR
def mwu(a, b):
    from scipy.stats import mannwhitneyu
    return mannwhitneyu(a, b, alternative="two-sided").pvalue

try:
    import scipy
    ct = scores_df.loc[scores_df.modality=="CT","score"].to_numpy()
    mr = scores_df.loc[scores_df.modality=="MR","score"].to_numpy()
    if len(ct) and len(mr):
        print(f"\nMannWhitney CT vs MR p={mwu(ct,mr):.3g}  (n_CT={len(ct)}, n_MR={len(mr)})")
except Exception as e:
    print("[note] scipy not installed for MWU:", e)

End-to-end evaluation & reporting (CV metrics, calibration, permutation test, CPTAC summary)¶
Purpose

Run a complete evaluation pipeline on MIDAS embeddings and produce a compact report:
1) cross-validated performance on MIDAS,

2) calibration diagnostics (reliability/ECE/Brier),

3) permutation test to confirm signal > chance,

4) summarize calibrated scores on CPTAC, and

5) auto-write a short conclusion markdown.




Inputs (produced earlier)¶
    

  • outputs/midas_clip_img_512.npy  MIDAS embeddings (N_photo, 512)  
    • 

  • outputs/midas_labels.npy  MIDAS binary labels (N_photo,)  
    • 

  • outputs/midas_128.npy, outputs/cptac_128.npy  shared 128-D arrays (not required for the CV here but asserted to exist)  
    • 

  • outputs/cptac_scores_calibrated.csv  CPTAC per-series calibrated scores/metadata
    • 



All files are sanity-checked via assert.




1) 5-fold cross-validation on MIDAS¶
    

  • Split: StratifiedKFold(n_splits=5, shuffle=True, random_state=0)  
    • 

  • Model: StandardScaler  LogisticRegression(lbfgs, C=1.0, max_iter=2000) inside a Pipeline  
    • 

  • Metrics: AUROC and PR-AUC (mean  std) computed from out-of-fold probabilities
    • 



Outputs


    

  • Printed lines:
    
 MIDAS 5-fold AUROC: <mean>  <std>
    
 MIDAS 5-fold PR-AUC: <mean>  <std>
    • 





2) Probability calibration diagnostics¶
    

  • Compute ECE (Expected Calibration Error) with 15 uniform bins  
    • 

  • Compute Brier score on out-of-fold predictions  
    • 

  • Plot reliability curve (sklearn.calibration_curve):
    
saved to outputs/midas_reliability_curve.png
    • 





3) Permutation test (AUROC)¶
    

  • Shuffle labels n=200 times; for each permutation run the same 5-fold procedure and record mean AUROC  
    • 

  • Estimate a permutation p-value as the proportion of null AUROCs  observed AUROC (add-one smoothing)  
    • 

  • Save a histogram figure to outputs/midas_perm_hist.png
    • 





4) CPTAC calibrated score summaries¶
    

  • Load cptac_scores_calibrated.csv (renames score  score_cal if needed)  
    • 

  • Produce concise tables:
      

    • by modality: n, median, p25, p75, and simple percentile CIs (2.5/97.5)  
      • 

    • by body_part: same statistics (top-10 by frequency)  
      • 

    

    • 

  • Save to:
      

    • outputs/summary_cptac_by_modality.csv  
      • 

    • outputs/summary_cptac_by_bodypart.csv
      • 

    

    • 





5) Auto-generated conclusion¶
    

  • Writes a short Markdown summary with: MIDAS AUROC/PR-AUC, calibration stats (ECE/Brier), permutation p-value, and pointers to the CPTAC summaries.  
    • 

  • File: outputs/final_report.md
    • 





Notes¶
    

  • If you have subject/lesion IDs, replace StratifiedKFold with a grouped split to prevent leakage.  
    • 

  • Logistic regression is a robust baseline; keep the scaler for stable convergence.  
    • 

  • Percentile CIs here are simple quantiles; switch to bootstrap if you want median CIs.
    •

OUT = Path("./outputs"); OUT.mkdir(exist_ok=True)

# Files produced earlier in this notebook workflow
MIDAS_EMB = OUT/"midas_clip_img_512.npy"      # (N_photo, 512)
MIDAS_Y   = OUT/"midas_labels.npy"            # (N_photo,)
CPTAC_128 = OUT/"cptac_128.npy"               # (N_series, 128)  <-- already saved earlier
MIDAS_128 = OUT/"midas_128.npy"               # (N_photo, 128)
CPTAC_SCORES_CAL = OUT/"cptac_scores_calibrated.csv"  # produced earlier

assert MIDAS_EMB.exists() and MIDAS_Y.exists(), "Missing MIDAS embeddings/labels."
assert MIDAS_128.exists() and CPTAC_128.exists(), "Missing shared 128-D arrays."
assert CPTAC_SCORES_CAL.exists(), "Missing calibrated CPTAC scores CSV."

X_midas = np.load(MIDAS_EMB)   # you can swap to np.load(MIDAS_128) if preferred
y_midas = np.load(MIDAS_Y).astype(int)

# === 1) 5-fold CV on MIDAS with leakage-safe grouping (optional) ===
# If you have a subject/lesion grouping array, put it here to prevent leakage.
# Otherwise we just do StratifiedKFold on labels.
SEED = 0
cv = StratifiedKFold(n_splits=5, shuffle=True, random_state=SEED)

# Simple, strong baseline: Standardize + L2 LogisticRegression
clf = make_pipeline(
    StandardScaler(with_mean=True, with_std=True),
    LogisticRegression(max_iter=2000, C=1.0, solver="lbfgs")
)

probs_cv = np.zeros(len(y_midas), dtype=float)
aucs, pras = [], []

for tr, te in cv.split(X_midas, y_midas):
    clf.fit(X_midas[tr], y_midas[tr])
    p = clf.predict_proba(X_midas[te])[:,1]
    probs_cv[te] = p
    aucs.append(roc_auc_score(y_midas[te], p))
    pras.append(average_precision_score(y_midas[te], p))

midas_auc_mean = float(np.mean(aucs)); midas_auc_std = float(np.std(aucs, ddof=1))
midas_pr_mean  = float(np.mean(pras)); midas_pr_std  = float(np.std(pras, ddof=1))

print(f" MIDAS 5-fold AUROC: {midas_auc_mean:.3f}  {midas_auc_std:.3f}")
print(f" MIDAS 5-fold PR-AUC: {midas_pr_mean:.3f}  {midas_pr_std:.3f}")

# === 2) Reliability curve + ECE on MIDAS ===
def expected_calibration_error(y_true, p_hat, n_bins=15):
    # bins equally spaced in [0,1]
    bins = np.linspace(0,1,n_bins+1)
    ece = 0.0
    for i in range(n_bins):
        m = (p_hat>=bins[i]) & (p_hat<bins[i+1] if i<n_bins-1 else p_hat<=bins[i+1])
        if m.sum()==0:
            continue
        acc = y_true[m].mean()
        conf = p_hat[m].mean()
        ece += (m.mean()) * abs(acc - conf)
    return float(ece)

ece = expected_calibration_error(y_midas, probs_cv, n_bins=15)
bs  = brier_score_loss(y_midas, probs_cv)

fracs_pos, mean_pred = calibration_curve(y_midas, probs_cv, n_bins=15, strategy="uniform")

plt.figure(figsize=(4.5,4))
plt.plot([0,1],[0,1], "--", lw=1, label="Perfect")
plt.plot(mean_pred, fracs_pos, marker="o", lw=1.5, label="MIDAS (CV)")
plt.xlabel("Mean predicted probability")
plt.ylabel("Fraction of positives")
plt.title(f"Reliability | ECE={ece:.3f}  Brier={bs:.3f}")
plt.legend()
plt.tight_layout()
plt.savefig(OUT/"midas_reliability_curve.png", dpi=150)
plt.show()

# === 3) Permutation test (AUROC) to show signal isnt by chance ===
def perm_auc_distribution(X, y, base_cv, n_perm=200, seed=0):
    rng = np.random.default_rng(seed)
    null_aucs = []
    for _ in range(n_perm):
        y_perm = rng.permutation(y)
        fold_aucs = []
        for tr, te in base_cv.split(X, y_perm):
            clf.fit(X[tr], y_perm[tr])
            p = clf.predict_proba(X[te])[:,1]
            fold_aucs.append(roc_auc_score(y_perm[te], p))
        null_aucs.append(np.mean(fold_aucs))
    return np.array(null_aucs)

null_aucs = perm_auc_distribution(X_midas, y_midas, cv, n_perm=200, seed=SEED)
p_perm = ( (null_aucs >= midas_auc_mean).sum() + 1 ) / (len(null_aucs) + 1)

plt.figure(figsize=(5,3.2))
plt.hist(null_aucs, bins=20, alpha=0.75, edgecolor="k")
plt.axvline(midas_auc_mean, color="r", lw=2, label=f"Observed AUROC={midas_auc_mean:.3f}")
plt.title(f"Permutation test (n={len(null_aucs)}) | p{p_perm:.4f}")
plt.xlabel("Mean AUROC (5-fold) under label shuffling")
plt.ylabel("Count")
plt.legend()
plt.tight_layout()
plt.savefig(OUT/"midas_perm_hist.png", dpi=150)
plt.show()

# === 4) Summarize CPTAC calibrated scores & produce a compact report ===
cptac = pd.read_csv(CPTAC_SCORES_CAL)  # expects columns: series_uid, modality, body_part, score_cal
# Fallback if your column name is 'score' not 'score_cal'
if "score_cal" not in cptac.columns and "score" in cptac.columns:
    cptac = cptac.rename(columns={"score":"score_cal"})

def summarize(df, key, k=8):
    g = (df.groupby(key)["score_cal"]
           .agg(n="size", median="median",
                p25=lambda x: np.percentile(x,25),
                p75=lambda x: np.percentile(x,75),
                ci2_5=lambda x: np.percentile(x,2.5),
                ci97_5=lambda x: np.percentile(x,97.5))
           .reset_index()
           .sort_values("median", ascending=False))
    return g.head(k)

by_mod = summarize(cptac, "modality", k=10)
by_bp  = summarize(cptac, "body_part", k=10)

print("\nBy modality:\n", by_mod.to_string(index=False))
print("\nBy body_part (top 10):\n", by_bp.to_string(index=False))

# Save tables
by_mod.to_csv(OUT/"summary_cptac_by_modality.csv", index=False)
by_bp.to_csv(OUT/"summary_cptac_by_bodypart.csv", index=False)

conclusion = f"""

- Calibration is modest (ECE **{ece:.3f}**, Brier **{bs:.3f}**); reliability curve saved to `outputs/midas_reliability_curve.png`.

- On CPTAC-CM (radiology), calibrated melanoma-relevance scores differ by modality; summary CSVs saved to
  `outputs/summary_cptac_by_modality.csv` and `outputs/summary_cptac_by_bodypart.csv`.

**Limitations:** small CPTAC sample (n={len(cptac)} series), single simple map from radiologyCLIP-text, and domain gap (photoCT/MR/PT).
**Next:** scale CPTAC to full cohort, add modality-aware encoders (e.g., CT-specific), and repeat CV with subject-level grouping to preclude leakage.
"""
(OUT/"final_report.md").write_text(conclusion.strip(), encoding="utf-8")

✅ Summary & Next Steps¶
What we demonstrated.

A compact, federated workflow that discovers, accesses, harmonizes, embeds, and evaluates cross-repository imaging data without centralizing raw data, using the MIDRC BIH paradigm.






📌 Key Outcomes¶
    

  • Federated access: Queried TCIA (CPTAC-CM) via NBIA API and Stanford AIMI (MRA-MIDAS) via SAS, staging pilot subsets into the BIH workspace with full provenance.
    • 

  • Harmonization: Normalized identifiers (series_uid, patient_id, lesion_id) and semantics (modality, body_part, series_desc) toward CDE/CDM alignment; built auditable manifests (CSV/JSON).
    • 

  • Representations:
      

    • CLIP (ViT-B/32) image embeddings for MIDAS photos (512-D).
      • 

    • ResNet50 radiology features (2048-D)  ridge map into CLIP-text space (512-D).
      • 

    • Shared 128-D space via PCA (+ optional label anchors); fast UMAP for visualization.
      • 

    

    • 

  • Evaluation:
      

    • MIDAS 5-fold: AUROC 0.651  0.016, PR-AUC 0.302  0.023 (logistic baseline over CLIP).  
      • 

    • CPTAC scoring: Calibrated melanoma-likeness distributions by modality and body part with bootstrap CIs; example contrast CT vs MR MannWhitney p = 0.000188.
      • 

    

    • 

  • Deliverables: Saved embeddings, models, scored tables, figures, and a concise outputs/final_report.md.
